result.formatted_address: 111 Ngong Ping Rd, Lantau Island, Hong Kong
result.name: Ngong Ping Village

reviews.text: Over crowded. The wait for the sky cable was incredibly long. Checked out some abandoned villages which were interesting. Some cool off the beaten track paths to be explored here

I love the ambience with the open air and the cobble stone path and the statues and temple and quaint looking shops! My kids enjoyed our visit to this place even after climbing those stairs to the Tian Tan Buddha!

Mind blowing view of Hong Kong islands connected with multiple sea links was one of the unique features of cable car.  Ngong ping village was a mountain carved into an urbanized village. Value for money experience.

It feels a bit odd to come to this place for visiting the Big Buddha and the first thing you meet is a 7/11. The Ngong Ping Village feels a bit tourist for my taste. However if your looking for that this is the place. Foods, drinks and souvenirs is all found here for a reasonable price. Toilets are ok. Ps, if you’re lucky you’ll meet some holy cows.

Me and my daughter thoroughly enjoyed our visit to this little village. As soon as we exited the cable car and started walking around we enjoyed everything there was to see. The village is pretty small so it's easy to get around in a short amount of time. Which, to me, is perfect since most people really need to budget their time when on vacation. We spent maybe a total of 4-5 hours touring the place including walking up to the Buddha as well as eating lunch. I would suggest visiting around December-January though (for those who prefer cooler temperatures). The only drawback to that is that it's peak season so there will be plenty of people. But other than that our trip there was enjoyable and relaxing, even with the climb to the Buddha. Plenty of places to choose from for eating/snacking. There are also quite a few booths that sells snacks and souvenirs around the area.
